or so. Which, I'll admit - used to make me very uncomfortable when I was  in Elementary and JHS. I remember one time I was watching TV and I saw something that I thought was &quot;bad&quot; or whatever and I said - &quot;Oh, thats GAY!&quot;<br>
<br>
He told me he found the usage offensive, and since I wasn't really trying to offend him, I agreed to stop using it. This was about 22 years ago...<br>
<br>
I don't recall, but I am pretty sure I wasn't trying to offend him. Funny how that didn't make a bit of difference though.<br>
<br>
I'll admit... The words previous (primary) usage and it's use as a reference to homosexuality was kind of confusing to me as a child. One of my favorite TV shows was the Flinstones. If you recall the words to the theme song, the last line is: <br>
<br>
&quot;We'll have a GAY old time!&quot;<br>
<br>
I am pretty sure they weren't referring to Fred and Barney's &quot;relationship&quot;, although I'll admit it is possible... After all, they did seem to prefer each others company to the company of their wives...<br>
<br>
On another note: It's funny how different two parts of the country can be. I remember my first real job. (Radio station intern - Southern California -  Late 80's) It would not have been acceptable to use the word GAY in this way, but the DJ's could (sorta). Anyone else would get fired for it. Hell, even they would get fired for it if they did it OFF the air. (/boggle) You couldn't talk about God either - at least not specifically. Wouldn't want to abuse / annoy or discriminate against the Taoists, Satanists, Pagan's, Hindu's, etc.<br>
<br>
Flash forward 15 years and move across the country with a major Fortune 50 Corporate Dinosaur. (***COUGH*** DEATHSTAR*** COUGH***) And the first time they cater food in for the Tech's the 4th line Supervisor leads the group in (what I can only describe as) a traditional Southern Baptist style ode to Jesus! <br>
<br>
Sweet mother! And companies were literally getting sued into bankruptcy in So Cal for doing the same thing a decade or more before.<br>
<br>
/shrug. Life is funny. Get used to it, and remember to /con first before using your favorite slang terms / religious invocations in public places...<br>
